ODE XXXI.

In B. c. 28 (25th October), Augustus dedicated a temple, with-a library attached, which he had built in honor of Apono, on the Palatine Hill, to commemorate his victory at Actium. After the ceremonies of the day of dedication were over, we may suppose Horace putting in his own claim to the god's favor in this Ode, in which he represents himself as offering a libation (whether in private or at the temple is uncertain), and asking for that which, according to Juvenal (x. 356), should be the end of all prayer, ‘ mens sffna in corpore sano!
